<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Hydroponic Fertilizer: The Reservoir-First Method</h1>

  <p class="tagline">
    The best hydroponic fertilizer is not the strongest bottle on the shelf. It is the nutrient program that lets you build a stable, complete, repeatable reservoir for the crop you are actually growing.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most indoor gardeners, the best hydroponic fertilizer is a complete formula that dissolves cleanly, includes micronutrients, matches your crop and system, and is simple enough to mix accurately every time.</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    In hydroponics, fertilizer is not just plant food. It is the root environment.
  </p>

  <p>
    Soil gardeners can get away with some imprecision because the soil buffers many small mistakes. In hydroponics, roots live directly in the solution you mix. If that solution is too strong, too weak, incomplete, poorly mixed, or out of pH range, the plant experiences the mistake immediately.
  </p>

  <p>
    That is why the best way to choose hydroponic fertilizer is reservoir-first. Before comparing bottles, ask whether the nutrient program will help you create a solution that is complete, measurable, stable, and appropriate for your crop.
  </p>

  <p>
    Lettuce and herbs can often use a simple complete nutrient. Tomatoes and peppers usually need more careful strength, calcium, magnesium, and crop-stage management. Larger systems often benefit from dry nutrients, while beginners usually do better with simple liquid formulas.
  </p>

  <p>
    The goal is not to buy the most complicated nutrient line. The goal is to choose a fertilizer program you can mix accurately, monitor with pH and EC, and use consistently without turning a simple grow into a chemistry project.
  </p>
</header>

