<section class="guideSection" id="reservoir-first">
  <h2>The Reservoir-First Method</h2>

  <p>
    Most hydroponic fertilizer mistakes start with the bottle. Gardeners compare NPK numbers, growth-stage labels, or brand promises before asking the more important question: what kind of reservoir will this product help me maintain?
  </p>

  <p>
    In hydroponics, the reservoir is the soil. It is where roots find nutrients, water, oxygen, and stability. The best fertilizer is the one that helps you create a solution your plants can live in day after day without constant guessing.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Reservoir Question</th>
          <th>Why It Matters</th>
          <th>Buying Implication</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Can you mix it accurately?</strong></td>
          <td>Inconsistent mixing creates inconsistent growth.</td>
          <td>Beginners should favor simple liquid nutrients or clear dry programs.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Is it complete beyond NPK?</strong></td>
          <td>Hydroponic plants cannot rely on soil reserves to supply missing nutrients.</td>
          <td>Choose formulas with secondary nutrients and micronutrients.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Can you monitor pH and EC?</strong></td>
          <td>Nutrients can be present but unavailable, or strong enough to stress roots.</td>
          <td>Buy meters before buying a complicated nutrient line.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Does it match the crop?</strong></td>
          <td>Lettuce, herbs, peppers, and tomatoes do not need the same feeding strategy.</td>
          <td>Use simple complete nutrients for greens and more flexible programs for fruiting crops.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Does it match the reservoir size?</strong></td>
          <td>A countertop jar and a large grow-tent reservoir have different cost and mixing needs.</td>
          <td>Liquid nutrients suit small systems; dry nutrients often make more sense at scale.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Does your water change the recipe?</strong></td>
          <td>Tap water is not blank water. Hardness and alkalinity can affect pH and nutrient balance.</td>
          <td>Account for water quality before adding supplements blindly.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    A nutrient program that looks impressive on the label is not automatically the best choice. The better choice is the one that helps you make the same good reservoir today, next week, and every time you mix again.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="label-trap">
  <h2>The Bottle Label Trap</h2>

  <p>
    Hydroponic fertilizer labels can make the product look like it is doing all the work. But plants do not grow in the bottle. They grow in the reservoir you create after mixing, measuring, adjusting pH, and maintaining the solution over time.
  </p>

  <p>
    That is why label claims should be translated into reservoir questions before you buy.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Label Promise</th>
          <th>What Actually Matters in the Reservoir</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>“For explosive growth”</strong></td>
          <td>Is the EC appropriate for the crop, root system, light level, and growth stage?</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>“Complete nutrient”</strong></td>
          <td>Does it include calcium, magnesium, sulfur, and micronutrients, not just NPK?</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>“Bloom formula”</strong></td>
          <td>Is the plant actually ready for fruiting-stage feeding, or is the recipe being pushed too soon?</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>“Cal-Mag included”</strong></td>
          <td>Does your source water and base nutrient still require adjustment?</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>“Easy to use”</strong></td>
          <td>Can you repeat the mix accurately every time without guessing?</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>“Professional formula”</strong></td>
          <td>Do you have the meters, measuring tools, and routine to manage it properly?</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    A strong fertilizer in an unstable reservoir is still an unstable grow. Before choosing the most advanced product, make sure you can mix, measure, and maintain the solution it creates.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="more-bottles">
  <h2>More Bottles Are Not Automatically Better</h2>

  <p>
    More nutrient parts do not automatically mean better plants. They mean more control, and more ways to make the same reservoir inconsistent.
  </p>

  <p>
    A one-part nutrient can be the best choice for lettuce, basil, herbs, Kratky jars, and small indoor systems because it reduces decisions. A two-part, three-part, or dry program becomes more useful when the crop actually needs more control and you are prepared to measure carefully.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Nutrient Complexity</th>
          <th>What You Gain</th>
          <th>What You Risk</th>
          <th>Best Use</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>One-part nutrient</strong></td>
          <td>Simplicity and repeatability.</td>
          <td>Less crop-stage flexibility.</td>
          <td>Greens, herbs, Kratky, and beginners.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Two-part nutrient</strong></td>
          <td>Better separation of ingredients and more control.</td>
          <td>More measuring and more chances to mix unevenly.</td>
          <td>General vegetables and mixed systems.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Three-part nutrient</strong></td>
          <td>More stage-based control.</td>
          <td>Chasing feed charts and over-adjusting.</td>
          <td>Growers managing different crop stages.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Dry nutrient program</strong></td>
          <td>Lower cost per gallon and strong scalability.</td>
          <td>Requires accurate weighing, mixing order, and pH/EC habits.</td>
          <td>Larger reservoirs and experienced growers.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    Start with the simplest nutrient program that can properly feed the crop you are growing. Upgrade complexity only when the crop, reservoir size, and your measuring routine justify it.
  </p>
</section>

