<section class="guideSection" id="one-part-vs-three-part">
  <h2>One-Part vs Two-Part vs Three-Part Hydroponic Nutrients</h2>

  <p>
    Hydroponic fertilizer programs usually become more flexible as they add more parts, but they also become easier to overcomplicate.
  </p>

  <p>
    More bottles do not automatically mean better plants. They mean more control, and more ways to make mistakes.
  </p>

  <h3>One-Part Hydroponic Nutrients</h3>

  <p>
    One-part nutrients are the simplest option. You add one product to water, mix thoroughly, check strength and pH, and feed the plants.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is usually the best starting point for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>lettuce</li>
    <li>basil</li>
    <li>herbs</li>
    <li>small Kratky jars</li>
    <li>countertop hydroponic systems</li>
    <li>beginner indoor setups</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The tradeoff is limited flexibility. A one-part nutrient may work very well for greens and herbs but feel less adaptable when tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, or fruiting crops need stronger stage-aware feeding.
  </p>

  <h3>Two-Part Hydroponic Nutrients</h3>

  <p>
    Two-part nutrients usually separate ingredients that do not store well together in concentrated form.
  </p>

  <p>
    This can improve calcium management and make the nutrient program more complete while still staying easier than a full three-part system.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two-part nutrients are a good middle ground for gardeners who want more control than a one-part bottle without managing a more complicated feeding chart.
  </p>

  <h3>Three-Part Hydroponic Nutrients</h3>

  <p>
    Three-part nutrients give the most flexibility among common liquid programs.
  </p>

  <p>
    They usually allow you to adjust feeding across different crop stages, such as vegetative growth, flowering, and fruiting.
  </p>

  <p>
    This flexibility is useful for mixed indoor gardens, but it also creates temptation to constantly adjust the recipe.
  </p>

  <p>
    For beginners, the risk is chasing the feed chart instead of watching the plants, checking pH, and monitoring EC.
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>The Simple Rule</h2>

    <p>
      Start with the simplest nutrient program that can properly feed the crop you are growing. Move to more parts only when you need more control.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h3>Which One Should Most Gardeners Choose?</h3>

  <p>
    If you are growing lettuce, basil, herbs, or small indoor greens, start with a complete one-part hydroponic nutrient.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you are growing tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, strawberries, or larger indoor vegetables, a two-part, three-part, or dry program usually gives better control.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="liquid-vs-dry">
  <h2>Liquid vs Dry Hydroponic Fertilizer</h2>

  <p>
    Hydroponic nutrients are usually sold either as liquid concentrates or dry soluble fertilizers.
  </p>

  <p>
    Liquid nutrients are easier for beginners. Dry nutrients are usually more economical and scalable once you are comfortable measuring accurately.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Fertilizer Format</th>
          <th>Main Advantage</th>
          <th>Main Tradeoff</th>
          <th>Best Fit</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Liquid nutrient</strong></td>
          <td>Easy to measure and mix.</td>
          <td>Higher cost per gallon.</td>
          <td>Beginners and small systems.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Dry soluble nutrient</strong></td>
          <td>Economical and scalable.</td>
          <td>Requires accurate weighing and mixing.</td>
          <td>Larger reservoirs and repeat growers.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>One-part liquid</strong></td>
          <td>Simplest feeding routine.</td>
          <td>Less crop-stage control.</td>
          <td>Lettuce, herbs, and Kratky jars.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Dry A/B program</strong></td>
          <td>Better control over calcium and nutrient balance.</td>
          <td>More setup knowledge required.</td>
          <td>Advanced growers and fruiting crops.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Liquid Nutrients Are Easier</h3>

  <p>
    Liquid nutrients are the easiest way to start because they do not require a gram scale or dry mixing routine.
  </p>

  <p>
    They are especially useful for:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>small reservoirs</li>
    <li>first-time hydroponic growers</li>
    <li>Kratky jars</li>
    <li>countertop systems</li>
    <li>LECA houseplants</li>
    <li>lettuce and herb setups</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The downside is cost. Liquid nutrients are convenient, but you are paying for water, packaging, and simplicity.
  </p>

  <h3>Dry Nutrients Are Better for Scale</h3>

  <p>
    Dry nutrients are usually a better value once you are mixing larger volumes or running hydroponics regularly.
  </p>

  <p>
    They are popular with growers who want lower cost per gallon and more control over the nutrient solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    The tradeoff is precision. Dry nutrients require careful measuring, correct mixing order, and more confidence with pH and EC.
  </p>

  <h3>Mixing Order Matters More With Dry Nutrients</h3>

  <p>
    Some nutrients are separated because they can react or fall out of solution if mixed incorrectly in concentrated form.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is one reason dry programs often separate base fertilizer, calcium nitrate, and magnesium sulfate.
  </p>

  <p>
    Always follow the product’s mixing instructions instead of dumping every dry ingredient together at once.
  </p>

  <h3>Which Format Should You Buy?</h3>

  <p>
    Choose liquid nutrients if you want ease and are growing a small system.
  </p>

  <p>
    Choose dry nutrients if you are mixing larger reservoirs, growing tomatoes or peppers regularly, or want better long-term cost control.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="crop-fit">
  <h2>Best Hydroponic Fertilizer for Greens, Herbs, Tomatoes, and Peppers</h2>

  <p>
    The best hydroponic fertilizer depends heavily on the crop.
  </p>

  <p>
    Leafy greens and herbs are usually much easier to feed than fruiting crops. Tomatoes and peppers need more careful nutrient strength, calcium management, and environmental stability.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Crop Type</th>
          <th>Best Fertilizer Approach</th>
