        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Basil and herbs</strong></td>
          <td>Complete vegetative nutrient at moderate strength</td>
          <td>Good for leafy growth and regular harvests.</td>
          <td>Overly strong fruiting-crop recipes.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Tomatoes</strong></td>
          <td>Complete program with calcium and EC monitoring</td>
          <td>Fruiting crops need stronger nutrient control.</td>
          <td>Weak greens-only formulas.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Peppers</strong></td>
          <td>Complete nutrient with steady calcium and magnesium</td>
          <td>Supports longer indoor growth and fruiting.</td>
          <td>Overfeeding early seedlings.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Strawberries</strong></td>
          <td>Carefully managed complete nutrient</td>
          <td>Needs steady feeding without excessive salts.</td>
          <td>Random high-nitrogen feeding.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>LECA houseplants</strong></td>
          <td>Low-strength complete nutrient</td>
          <td>Works better for slower houseplant growth.</td>
          <td>Heavy hydroponic bloom boosters.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Lettuce and Leafy Greens</h3>

  <p>
    Lettuce, bok choy, spinach-style greens, and many leafy crops usually do well with a simple complete hydroponic nutrient.
  </p>

  <p>
    These crops are often the best starting point for new hydroponic growers because they grow quickly and do not require fruiting-stage nutrient management.
  </p>

  <p>
    Keep the solution mild, stable, and clean rather than pushing high strength.
  </p>

  <h3>Herbs</h3>

  <p>
    Basil, cilantro, parsley, mint, and other herbs usually need steady vegetative growth rather than aggressive bloom feeding.
  </p>

  <p>
    A complete hydroponic nutrient at moderate strength is usually a better fit than a heavy fruiting formula.
  </p>

  <p>
    Herbs can also show stress quickly if the system gets too hot, too strong, or poorly oxygenated.
  </p>

  <h3>Tomatoes</h3>

  <p>
    Tomatoes are much more demanding than lettuce.
  </p>

  <p>
    They need stronger light, more root space, more stable water uptake, and a nutrient program that handles calcium and fruiting demand.
  </p>

  <p>
    A simple greens nutrient may grow a tomato plant, but it is usually not the best choice for a productive indoor tomato crop.
  </p>

  <h3>Peppers</h3>

  <p>
    Peppers need patience and consistency.
  </p>

  <p>
    They can be slower than tomatoes indoors and often respond poorly to aggressive feeding when young.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use a complete nutrient program, monitor strength, and avoid pushing the plants too hard before the root system is ready.
  </p>

  <h3>LECA Houseplants</h3>

  <p>
    Houseplants grown in LECA or semi-hydro setups usually need weaker, steadier feeding than vegetables grown for fast harvest.
  </p>

  <p>
    A mild complete nutrient is usually more appropriate than a high-strength production formula.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="ph-ec">
  <h2>pH, EC, and Fertilizer Strength</h2>

  <p>
    Hydroponic fertilizer choice matters, but pH and EC determine whether the nutrient solution is actually usable.
  </p>

  <p>
    In soil, the growing medium buffers many mistakes. In hydroponics, the nutrient solution is much more direct. If the pH or fertilizer strength is off, plants can show problems quickly.
  </p>

  <h3>pH Affects Nutrient Availability</h3>

  <p>
    pH influences which nutrients plants can access from the solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    If pH drifts too far out of range, nutrients may be present in the reservoir but less available to the plant.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why deficiency symptoms are not always solved by adding more fertilizer.
  </p>

  <h3>EC Measures Solution Strength</h3>

  <p>
    EC is a way to estimate how strong the dissolved nutrient solution is.
  </p>

  <p>
    A very low EC can mean the plants are underfed. A very high EC can stress roots, burn leaf tips, or make water uptake harder.
  </p>

  <p>
    EC does not tell you the exact balance of every nutrient, but it is one of the most useful tools for avoiding obvious underfeeding or overfeeding.
  </p>

  <h3>Fertilizer Strength Should Match the Crop Stage</h3>

  <p>
    Seedlings, leafy greens, herbs, and fruiting vegetables do not all need the same nutrient strength.
  </p>

  <p>
    Young plants usually need weaker feeding. Mature fruiting crops can usually handle more, but only when light, roots, oxygen, and environment are strong enough to support that growth.
  </p>

  <h3>Water Quality Changes the Starting Point</h3>

  <p>
    Tap water is not blank water.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hard water, high alkalinity, dissolved minerals, and existing calcium or magnesium can all change how your nutrient solution behaves.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is one reason two gardeners can use the same fertilizer and get different results.
  </p>

  <h3>Do Not Diagnose Everything From Leaves Alone</h3>

  <p>
    Yellowing, curling, tip burn, and stunting can be caused by nutrient problems, but they can also come from pH drift, weak light, poor oxygen, root disease, heat stress, or old solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before adding more fertilizer, check the basics:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>pH</li>
    <li>EC</li>
    <li>water temperature</li>
    <li>root appearance</li>
    <li>light strength</li>
    <li>airflow</li>
    <li>reservoir age</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>The Reservoir Rule</h2>

    <p>
      In hydroponics, “how much fertilizer?” is not answered by the bottle alone. It is answered by the crop, the water, the reservoir, the light, and the meter.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="guideSection" id="cal-mag">
  <h2>Calcium, Magnesium, and Micronutrients</h2>

  <p>
    A good hydroponic fertilizer needs more than nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hydroponic plants also need secondary nutrients and micronutrients because they cannot rely on soil biology or mineral reserves to fill in the gaps.
  </p>

  <h3>NPK Is Not Enough</h3>

  <p>
    The NPK number on a fertilizer label tells you about nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium, but hydroponic crops also need nutrients such as calcium, magnesium, sulfur, iron, manganese, boron, zinc, copper, and molybdenum.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why a complete hydroponic nutrient is usually a better choice than a basic fertilizer with a reasonable-looking NPK ratio.
  </p>

  <h3>Calcium Matters for Fruiting Crops</h3>

  <p>
    Tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, and other fruiting crops are especially sensitive to calcium and water-uptake problems.
  </p>

  <p>
    Calcium issues often show up as distorted new growth, weak growing tips, or fruit-quality problems.
  </p>

  <p>
    But calcium problems are not always solved by simply adding more calcium. Poor water movement, pH issues, root stress, heat, high EC, and inconsistent uptake can all create calcium-related symptoms.
  </p>

  <h3>Magnesium Supports Healthy Green Growth</h3>

  <p>
    Magnesium is important for chlorophyll and healthy leaf function.
  </p>

  <p>
    Many dry hydroponic nutrient programs include magnesium sulfate as part of the full recipe because magnesium is a meaningful part of the nutrient balance.
  </p>

  <h3>Cal-Mag Is Not a Universal Fix</h3>

  <p>
    Cal-Mag supplements can be useful in the right situation, but they are often overused.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before adding Cal-Mag automatically, check:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>your base nutrient formula</li>
    <li>your water quality</li>
    <li>pH</li>
    <li>EC</li>
    <li>root health</li>
    <li>crop stage</li>
    <li>whether symptoms match a true calcium or magnesium issue</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Adding supplements blindly can raise EC and create new problems.
  </p>

  <h3>Micronutrients Are Easy to Forget</h3>

  <p>
    Iron and other micronutrients are needed in small amounts, but they still matter.
  </p>

  <p>
    A complete hydroponic nutrient should include a micronutrient package so you are not relying only on NPK and hoping the rest appears from the water.
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>The Complete Nutrient Check</h2>

    <p>
      When comparing hydroponic fertilizers, look for a complete formula designed for hydroponics, not just a familiar NPK number.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="system-fit">
  <h2>Hydroponic Fertilizer for Kratky, DWC, NFT, LECA, and Grow Tents</h2>

  <p>
    The best fertilizer also depends on the hydroponic system.
  </p>

  <p>
