  <h3>Kratky Systems</h3>

  <p>
    Kratky systems work best with a simple complete nutrient that is easy to mix consistently.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because the system is passive, avoid constant tinkering. Start with a clean complete formula, mix accurately, and choose crops that fit the reservoir size.
  </p>

  <h3>DWC Systems</h3>

  <p>
    Deep water culture relies heavily on solution quality because roots sit in the reservoir environment.
  </p>

  <p>
    Use a complete hydroponic nutrient, monitor pH and EC, and remember that oxygen, water temperature, and root health are just as important as fertilizer strength.
  </p>

  <h3>NFT Systems</h3>

  <p>
    NFT systems need clean, soluble nutrients because solution is constantly moving through narrow channels.
  </p>

  <p>
    Avoid products that leave heavy residue or organic buildup unless the system is specifically designed to handle them.
  </p>

  <h3>LECA and Semi-Hydro</h3>

  <p>
    LECA houseplants usually do better with mild, steady feeding than strong vegetable-production recipes.
  </p>

  <p>
    Keep nutrient strength moderate, flush when needed, and watch for salt buildup over time.
  </p>

  <h3>Grow Tents</h3>

  <p>
    In a grow tent, fertilizer interacts with light, heat, humidity, airflow, and watering demand.
  </p>

  <p>
    Stronger lights and faster growth can increase nutrient and water demand, but poor airflow or high heat can make overfeeding symptoms worse.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    For tent setup, see <a href="/guides/best-grow-tent/">best grow tent</a> and <a href="/guides/best-grow-lights-for-seedlings/">best grow lights for seedlings</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="mixing">
  <h2>Mixing, Measuring, and Feeding Schedule Basics</h2>

  <p>
    Hydroponic fertilizer works best when mixing becomes repeatable.
  </p>

  <p>
    The exact recipe depends on the product label, crop, and system, but the basic workflow is similar for most home hydroponic setups.
  </p>

  <h3>1. Start With Clean Water</h3>

  <p>
    Start with water you understand as much as possible.
  </p>

  <p>
    Tap water, filtered water, and reverse-osmosis water all behave differently. If your water is very hard or has high alkalinity, it can affect pH and nutrient balance.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Add Nutrients in the Correct Order</h3>

  <p>
    Follow the product directions carefully.
  </p>

  <p>
    This matters especially with multi-part and dry nutrient programs. Some components should not be mixed together in concentrated form.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Mix Thoroughly</h3>

  <p>
    Give each nutrient component time to dissolve and disperse before adding the next part.
  </p>

  <p>
    Uneven mixing can create inaccurate readings and inconsistent feeding.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Check EC</h3>

  <p>
    EC helps you understand the overall strength of the nutrient solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    Start lower with seedlings and sensitive crops, then increase only when the crop, light, and root system can support stronger growth.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Adjust pH After Nutrients Are Mixed</h3>

  <p>
    Nutrients can change the pH of the water.
  </p>

  <p>
    Mix the nutrient solution first, then check and adjust pH according to the crop and system guidance.
  </p>

  <h3>6. Monitor Drift Over Time</h3>

  <p>
    pH and EC can change as plants take up water and nutrients.
  </p>

  <p>
    A stable reservoir still needs periodic checks, especially in warm rooms, small reservoirs, or fast-growing crops.
  </p>

  <h3>7. Top Off Carefully</h3>

  <p>
    When water levels drop, do not automatically replace all lost volume with full-strength nutrient solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plants may be taking up water and nutrients at different rates. Check EC before deciding whether to add plain water, dilute nutrient solution, or a fresh reservoir mix.
  </p>

  <h3>8. Replace the Solution When Needed</h3>

  <p>
    Over time, reservoirs can become imbalanced even if the EC number looks acceptable.
  </p>

  <p>
    Periodic reservoir changes help reset the solution, reduce buildup, and keep the system easier to manage.
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>The Mixing Rule</h2>

    <p>
      Measure consistently, mix in the right order, check EC, then adjust pH. Do not guess your way through hydroponic feeding.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="mistakes">
  <h2>Common Hydroponic Fertilizer Mistakes</h2>

  <p>
    Most hydroponic fertilizer problems come from using the wrong product, mixing too strong, ignoring pH and EC, or treating every symptom as a reason to add more nutrients.
  </p>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Mistake</th>
          <th>Why It Causes Problems</th>
          <th>Better Approach</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>

      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Using soil fertilizer</strong></td>
          <td>It may not dissolve or balance properly in hydroponic systems.</td>
          <td>Use fertilizer designed for hydroponics.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Choosing by NPK only</strong></td>
          <td>Ignores calcium, magnesium, and micronutrients.</td>
          <td>Choose a complete nutrient formula.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Ignoring pH</strong></td>
          <td>Nutrients may be present but less available.</td>
          <td>Check and adjust pH after mixing.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Ignoring EC</strong></td>
          <td>You may overfeed or underfeed without realizing it.</td>
          <td>Use an EC meter for nutrient strength.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Overfeeding seedlings</strong></td>
          <td>Young roots are sensitive to strong solution.</td>
          <td>Start mild and increase gradually.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Mixing concentrates together</strong></td>
          <td>Some nutrients can react or precipitate.</td>
          <td>Add each part to water separately according to the label.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Using bloom boosters too early</strong></td>
          <td>Can unbalance nutrition before plants are ready.</td>
          <td>Match feeding to crop stage.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Adding Cal-Mag blindly</strong></td>
          <td>Can raise EC and create imbalance.</td>
          <td>Check water quality, base nutrient, pH, and symptoms first.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Never changing the reservoir</strong></td>
          <td>Solution balance can drift over time.</td>
          <td>Refresh the reservoir when needed.</td>
        </tr>

        <tr>
          <td><strong>Chasing deficiency charts too quickly</strong></td>
          <td>Leaf symptoms can have many causes.</td>
          <td>Check pH, EC, roots, light, and environment first.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="troubleshooting">
  <h2>Troubleshooting Hydroponic Nutrient Problems</h2>

  <p>
    Hydroponic nutrient issues can look similar even when the causes are different.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before adding more fertilizer, check pH, EC, roots, water temperature, light strength, and reservoir age.
  </p>

  <div class="troubleshootingGrid">
    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Leaves Are Yellowing</h3>

      <p>
        Yellowing can come from low nitrogen, pH problems, old solution, weak light, root stress, or poor oxygen.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>What to check:</strong> pH, EC, root color, light strength, and whether the reservoir is overdue for a change.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> correct the root cause before simply adding more fertilizer.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Leaf Tips Are Burning</h3>

      <p>
        Burnt tips often point to solution strength that is too high, salt buildup, or environmental stress making uptake harder.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>What to check:</strong> EC, water level, reservoir age, airflow, and heat.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> reduce strength if needed and refresh the reservoir if buildup is likely.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Tomatoes or Peppers Show Fruit Problems</h3>

      <p>
        Fruiting problems are often blamed on a single missing nutrient, but water uptake, calcium movement, heat, roots, and EC all matter.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>What to check:</strong> pH, EC, calcium source, water consistency, root health, and heat stress.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> stabilize the system instead of adding random supplements.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>pH Keeps Drifting</h3>

      <p>
        pH drift can come from water alkalinity, plant uptake, reservoir biology, nutrient balance, or an inconsistent adjustment routine.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>What to check:</strong> source water, reservoir size, nutrient mix, and how often you top off.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> track the pattern and adjust based on measured changes, not guesses.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Plants Are Stunted</h3>

      <p>
        Stunting can be caused by weak nutrients, excessive nutrients, cold solution, low oxygen, weak light, or root problems.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>What to check:</strong> EC, pH, water temperature, root appearance, light intensity, and airflow.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> improve the limiting condition rather than assuming fertilizer is the only issue.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="troubleshootingCard">
      <h3>Roots Look Brown or Slimy</h3>

      <p>
        Brown roots are not always a fertilizer problem. Oxygen, water temperature, disease pressure, organic buildup, and old solution can all affect root health.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>What to check:</strong> aeration, reservoir temperature, smell, solution age, and cleanliness.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>Fix:</strong> improve oxygen and sanitation before increasing fertilizer strength.
      </p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="guideSection" id="final-recommendation">
  <h2>Final Buying Recommendation</h2>

  <p>
    For most beginners growing lettuce, herbs, and small indoor vegetables, start with a simple complete hydroponic nutrient before moving into multi-part programs.
  </p>

  <p>
    For tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, strawberries, and larger systems, choose a complete two-part, three-part, or dry soluble program that gives better control over calcium, magnesium, micronutrients, and crop-stage feeding.
  </p>

  <p>
    The best hydroponic fertilizer is the nutrient program that helps you build a stable reservoir: complete enough for the crop, easy enough to mix accurately, and measurable enough to manage with pH and EC instead of guessing.
  </p>

  <div class="calloutBox">
    <h2>Before You Buy, Check These Five Things</h2>

    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Crop type:</strong> greens and herbs are easier than tomatoes and peppers.</li>
      <li><strong>System size:</strong> small reservoirs favor liquid nutrients; larger systems may favor dry nutrients.</li>
      <li><strong>Completeness:</strong> look beyond NPK and check for secondary nutrients and micronutrients.</li>
      <li><strong>Measuring comfort:</strong> do not buy a program you cannot mix accurately.</li>
      <li><strong>pH and EC:</strong> plan to measure the solution, not guess.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    A simple complete nutrient is often the smartest first purchase. More advanced nutrient programs are useful when you actually need more control and have the meters, routine, and crop demands to justify them.
  </p>

  <p>
    In hydroponics, the label matters less than the reservoir you create. Plants do not grow in nutrient marketing claims. They grow in the solution around their roots.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Buy for the crop, the system, the water, and your ability to measure — not just the strongest promise on the bottle.
  </p>
</section>